Malcolm Ross Kinsella Ryan wrote:
>
>It is with great regret that I vote against Plots, which I have campaigned
>for for so long, but I just don't think it fits into our current economic
>environment. VT supply is finely balanced at last, Plots will throw it
>out of kilter again. I still think we need some way to encourage 
>specialisation of production, but I don't think Plots are the right way
>anymore.

VT supply is in much better shape that it has been, but finely
balanced it is not quite yet. Salaries put about 21 VTs/week into
the economy, and unemployment benefits about another 5. R833 has
been adding about another 4 VTs/week, but your Proposal to amend
it has just taken effect. So let's say that roughly 26 VTs/week 
are entering circulation. Now, my recent amendment to R955 has
succeeded, I think, in increasing VT expenditure somewhat, but
still I'd say that only 10-15 VTs a week are being spent voting on
Proposals. So before the effect of Plots is considered, there's
still a gap of about 11-16 VTs/week between inputs and expenditure.
That's a lot better than it has been in the past, but we've still
work to do. Of course I agree with you that the adoption of Plots is
is a step backwards that is only going to make things worse.

However, my Proposal 'The Levers of Monetary Policy' offers the
prospect of some relief from this situation, since the Chancellor
will be able to reduce the BOS in response to VT oversupply. The
adoption of Plots unfortunately halves the length of this lever,
with Plots in place, Salaries will only account for about half
of VT supply. Even reducing Salaries to zero may not be enough
to counter the effect of Plots, if they are used to maximum effect.
It will be interesting to see how the Chancellor responds to
conflicting political pressures to reign in supply on the one hand,
and pay Officers for the work they do on the other. And if things
get too out of hand, the Accountor can use the other lever of taxes
to keep VTs scarce while we work on the balancing problem. The upshot
is that the adoption of Plots has made the adoption of 'The Levers
of Monetary Policy' even more urgent, and I repeat my call for
Players with P-Notes to spend some of them raising the Priority
of this Proposal to 3 before the end of the Week. I'd do it myself,
but I have no P-Notes. 

I'll tell you what: I'll offer 2 VTs to each Player who spends a
P-Note to raise the Priority of 'Levers', until its Priority is 3.

Any takers?

